body:
**What happened**:

On a resource with managedFields populated, a no-op patch modified the serialization order of managedFields.

**What you expected to happen**:

No-op patches do not result in a write to etcd.

**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:

```
# capture watch events
kubectl get deployment -o yaml -w --output-watch-events > watch.txt &

# create deployment
kubectl create deployment foo --image=foo

# record pre-patch state
kubectl get deployment/foo -o yaml > 1.txt

# no-op patch deployment updated resourceVersion, reordered kubectl and kube-controller-manager fields
kubectl patch deployments/foo -n default --type=merge -p '{}'
# record post-patch state
kubectl get deployment/foo -o yaml > 2.txt

# second no-op patch is an actual no-op
kubectl patch deployments/foo -n default --type=merge -p '{}'
# record result
kubectl get deployment/foo -o yaml > 3.txt
```

watch.txt contains:
* the initial ADDED event from kubectl
* MODIFIED events from kube-controller-manager
* one MODIFIED event corresponding to the kubectl patch (from resourceVersion 1704 in 1.txt to resourceVersion 1718 in 2.txt)

